</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><bold>Jula</bold><space/>(<bold>Dyula, Dioula</bold>) is a<space/><link><target>Mande languages</target><part>Mande language</part></link><space/>spoken in<space/><link><target>Burkina Faso</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Ivory Coast</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Mali</target></link>. It is one of the<space/><link><target>Manding languages</target></link>, and is most closely related to<space/><link><target>Bambara language</target><part>Bambara</part></link>, being<space/><link><target>mutually intelligible</target></link><space/>with Bambara as well as<space/><link><target>Eastern Maninka language</target><part>Malinke</part></link>. It is a<space/><link><target>trade language</target></link><space/>in<space/><link><target>West Africa</target></link><space/>and is spoken by millions of people, either as a first or second language. It is written in the<space/><link><target>Arabic script</target></link><space/>and the<space/><link><target>Latin script</target></link>, as well as in the indigenous<space/><link><target>N'Ko alphabet</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>A<space/><link><target>movie</target></link><space/>spoken in Dyula is<space/><link><target>Fanta Rgina Nacro</target></link>'s<space/><italics><link><target>Night of Truth</target></link></italics>.</paragraph><heading level='2'>External links</heading><paragraph><template><target>Incubator</target><arg name="code"><space/>dyu</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Dyula people</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>Reflist</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Languages of Burkina Faso</target></template><template><target>Languages of Ivory Coast</target></template><template><target>Languages of the Gambia</target></template><template><target>Mande languages</target></template></paragraph><p